\begin{slide}[toc=Intro,bm=Intro]{Introduction \& Terminology}
\begin{description}
\item[Threat Landscape] The elements typically \textbf{outside of your control} that impact your
                        security posture. This is where your threat actors, geopolitical policies,
                        third-party postures, and similar factors exist\vspace{0.25in}
\item[Attack Surface] The elements \textbf{within your control/influence} impacting your security
                      posture. Includes: Network design, user behavior, site geographies, security
                      tools, etc. Considered frequently to be what you're defending against the
                      \textbf{Threat Landscape}\vspace{0.25in}
\item[Cyber Intelligence] Knowledge of your threat landscape \& attack surface. This can be in the
                          form of structured/unstructured documentation, threat databases, tribal
                          knowledge, situational awareness, and other formats
\end{description}
\end{slide}

